{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"539b7d2d-f2c0-4ebb-84ec-5d04eedac6bf","content":"The template is **functional but not fully ready** for NuGet publishing. Here's what I found:\n\n**Present & correct:** `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `sourceName`, `author`, `classifications`, `tags`, `symbols` — all look good.\n\n**Missing for publish-readiness:**\n\n| Field | Why it matters |\n|---|---|\n| `$schema` | Enables validation & IntelliSense (`https://json.schemastore.org/template`) |\n| `description` | Critical for NuGet discoverability — users won't know what the template does |\n| `groupIdentity` | Lets multiple versions of the template coexist in a package (e.g. `MyCompany.WebApi.CSharp`) |\n| `precedence` | Works with `groupIdentity` to control version ordering |\n| `defaultName` | Sets the default project name when the user doesn't specify one (e.g. `WebApi1`) |\n\n**Recommendation:** At minimum, add `description` and `groupIdentity` before publishing. Without a `description`, the template will be nearly invisible on NuGet. Would you like me to add these fields?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b01b8536-246c-41c2-bbfb-a4cdbbbcd92e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check for required and recommended fields per the .NET template engine spec.\n\nKey issues I see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required but strongly recommended for validation/IntelliSense.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet package templates so multiple versions can coexist.\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Related to groupIdentity for version ordering.\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Common for project templates.\n5. **The `defaultValue` for Framework is `net9.0`** but this should be fine.\n\n\n6. **Missing `description`** — Highly recommended for NuGet discoverability; without it, users won't understand the template's purpose.\n\nLooking at the official spec, the truly required fields are `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, and `author` — all of which are present. The `sourceName` replacement target is set to `MyWebApi`, which should work fine as long as the project files reference that name.\n\nHowever, there are some important gaps for NuGet publishing: `groupIdentity` is missing (needed for organizing related templates), `defaultName` isn't specified (so users have to provide a project name), and `$schema` would help with validation. The template functions, but it's not quite ready for NuGet distribution without these additions.","outputTokens":659,"requestId":"A856:2211CA:711424A:7C95BA1:69F15796"},"id":"b856f48e-ef22-4240-8a2c-abbbd5ecad3f","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:58:12.728Z","parentId":"db5d8b0f-c602-4a5f-ab11-7fb55bb3fc46"}
